  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 최상의 …… 속한다 : '
    value: 진(晉)나라 왕이보(王夷甫)가 어린 아이들이 죽었는데, 산간(山簡)이 조상하러 갔더니, 왕이 보는 애통을 누르지 못하였다. 산간이 말하기를, “품에 있던 어린 것이 죽었는데, 이렇게 애통할 것이 무엇인가.” 한즉, 왕이보는 답하기를, 본문(本文)에 있는 말과 같이 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 복자하(卜子夏)가 …… 책망 : '
    value: 공자(孔子)의 제자 자하(子夏)가 아들을 잃고 애통하여 눈이 멀었다. 증자(曾子)가 가서 책하기를, “너는 세 가지 죄가 있다. 네가 서하(西河)에 사는데 서하 사람들이 너를 부자(夫子 공자(孔子))보다 나은 줄 의심하니 그것이 한 가지 죄요, 너의 부모가 죽었을 때에는 이렇게 애통하였다는 말을 듣지 못하였으니 두 가지 죄요, 네가 자식이 죽었음으로 하여 눈이 멀었으니, 세 가지 죄이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 이최(二衰) : '
    value: 상복(喪服)의 참최(斬衰)ㆍ재최(齋衰)를 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 삼상(三殤) : '
    value: 상(殤)은 미성년 자의 죽음에 대한 말인데, 《의례》상복전(喪服傳)에, “16세에서 19세까지는 장상(長殤), 12세에서 15세까지는 중상(中殤), 8세에서 11세까지는 하상(下殤)이요, 8세 이하는 복이 없다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 애일(愛日) : '
    value: 자식이 부모를 섬기는 날을 애일이라 한다. 법언(法言)에, “오래도록 할 수 없는 것은 어버이를 섬기는 일이므로 효자는 날을 아낀다[不可得而久者 事親之謂也 孝子愛日].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 의려(倚閭) : '
    value: 어머니가 자식을 기다리는 데 쓰는 말이다. 《국책(國策)》제책(齊策)에 왕손가(王孫賈)의 어머니가 왕손가더러 말하기를, “네가 아침에 나가서 늦도록 돌아오지 않으면 나는 방문에 기대어 바라보고, 네가 저물녘에 나가서 돌아오지 않으면 대문간에 기대어 바라본다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 척호(陟岵) : '
    value: 자식이 부모를 사모하는데 쓰는 말이다. 《시경(詩經)》위풍(魏風)에, “저산 올라가서 아버지를 바라본다[陟彼岵兮 瞻望父兮].”에서 나온 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 춘휘(春暉) : '
    value: 봄철의 따뜻한 볕을 들어 부모의 은혜에 비유한 것. 맹교(孟郊) 의 〈유자음(遊子吟)〉에, “어느 뉘라 촌초(寸草)만한 정성으로 봄볕 같은 은혜를 갚는다 하리[誰言寸草心 報得三春暉].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 풍수(風樹) : '
    value: 어버이가 돌아가서 모시지 못하는 데 쓰는 말이다. 고어(皐魚)의 말에, “나무는 고요하고 싶지만 바람이 그쳐 주지 않고, 자식은 봉양하고 싶지만 어버이가 기다려 주지 않는다[樹欲靜而風不止 子欲養而親不待].”에서 인용한 것임.
  - key: '[주-D010] 과기(瓜期) : '
    value: 관직의 임기를 말한 것이다. 《좌전》 장공(莊公) 8년에, 제후(齊侯)가 연칭(連稱) 관지부(管至父)를 규구(葵丘)로 보내면서, “오이 먹는 철에 가니 명년 오이 먹을 철에 교대하라[瓜時而往 及瓜而還].”를 인용한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 거문고 …… 가지고 : '
    value: 송(宋)나라 사람 조변(趙抃)이 외직으로 나가 성도(成都)를 다스리는데, 자기에게 딸린 것은 거문고 하나, 학 한 마리뿐이며, 간편한 정사를 하였다. 그래서 수령(守令)의 청백함을 말할 때 흔히 쓴다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 유애(遺愛) : '
    value: 인애(仁愛)의 덕이 갈려 간 후에 남아 있다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D013] 이런 …… 경험[折臂]했습니다 : '
    value: 주나라 성왕(成王)이, “세 번 팔목이 부러진 까닭에 의사가 되었다[三折臂成醫].”는 말을 인용한 것인데, 난경을 겪었다는 말이다.
english:
  title: A Letter Urging the Retention of Kim Jong-jik as Governor of Hamyang
  author: Kang Hi-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    How fares your health? My longing for you grows ever more keen. I heard that your carriage was departing, and I took up a flask of wine, intending to bid you farewell by the banks of the Sageum River. But then I learned you were waiting to consult the inspector. Days passed in delay, and still your carriage departed. When I heard you had submitted your resignation, I feared that if you yielded to the high official's repeated entreaties, you would be separated from us, and our reunion would become uncertain. My heart grows heavy with sorrow that no brush or tongue can fully express.

    I offer a thought or two for your consideration, if you will but hear me. The ancients said: "The highest nature forgets emotion, the lowest understands it not, and emotion's true dwelling is with us." Though I cannot say precisely whom "us" designates, yet observing human nature, all creatures with blood and breath possess compassion as Heaven's constant gift, with love flowing especially rich. This is the very heart by which Heaven and Earth nurture all things. Without this heart, creation itself might cease. Thus parents will brave fire and water to save their children from calamity, will risk all for their advancement—yet at the threshold between life and death, each soul has its appointed span. Even parents cannot cross this boundary; should love overstep propriety here, it transforms to sorrow, and few escape losing their way. This is why Zi Xia lost his sight through excessive grief for his son, and why the Sage's school finally reproached him.

    The Sage established ritual to govern human feeling. For parents, he ordained the two grades of mourning; for children, the three categories of untimely death. These must not be violated by a hair's breadth. Should a gentleman follow the impulse of his heart alone, grief for a child would exceed that for parents—would this not contradict the Way of propriety?

    Your honor possesses complete virtue and abundant talent. The palace and the archives both keep seats empty for you. Yet to send you to govern a remote, humble county—is this not Heaven's special favor? Truly, because the Sage-King practices filial piety in his rule, and your aged mother dwells at home, he grants you this county that you might fulfill the "love of days." To resign from this and retire to the countryside would be unthinkable. Should you resign and return home, by tomorrow the court will surely hear of it. If the court summons you to office, how then will you proceed? To plead illness borders on deception; to firmly decline offers no excuse. You would be forced to respond and journey to the capital, thereby separating from your mother's side. The wait at the gate and the gazing from the hill would bring suffering surpassing even the grief of losing a child. In such circumstance, is not the remote Cheonryeong preferable to serving a thousand *li* from home?

    Thus your present course, intended to bring your mother peace, may instead become a burden. Alas, spring's warmth cannot be held; the wind through trees brings sorrow. How many have squandered their years in official service north and south, losing the precious moments of filial duty! Should this not strike us with dread? Yet your term still has a year remaining. With a single zither and a single crane, rest at ease in the magistrate's quarters, inquire each morning and evening after your mother's health, and should she fall ill, you may return in a day's journey. At the same time, Cheonryeong's people will enjoy one more year of your benevolence. Is this not to fulfill both loyalty and filial piety?

    Yet I recall the great principle of withdrawal and engagement. Confucius departed his post without even removing his official robes; Mencius took three days to cross the border. Though their paces differed, their intentions were plain. Never have I heard of one abandoning office from fear of calamity or family misfortune.

    I understand well that you fear your mother's sorrow will sicken her, and so you wish to tend her constantly. Yet Cheonryeong's people know not your true purpose. They harbor only your lingering kindness, saying to me: "Our worthy governor resigns because he cannot bear his grief," or "He flees some curse and will soon return to comfort us." They wander lost like infants deprived of milk, seeking solace in darkness. Were I as humble as they suppose, I would not act thus—how much less you!

    Yet the words of others are endless, and I fear they may tarnish your great principle. Though I am insignificant, I have tasted such sorrow. Within three years, I lost four sons in succession. Though I steeled myself, emotion overtook reason: my throat tightened, my eyes dimmed as if veiled, thorns seemed to lodge in my throat, and I could neither swallow nor cry out. Finding no solace in heaven or earth, I sold my ancestral home to escape the traces of my children's play. Yet this brought only temporary respite. When memory returned, so did the pain—as the poet Chen Quanfei wrote, though we know such grief is illusion, when it comes we cannot resist it. Now, more than a decade has passed, and still some sorrow lingers. How much more must you endure!

    Though my words may seem foolish and unheeded, know that emotion, when governed by ritual and propriety without losing proper form, will in time grow settled and find its measure. I humbly lay before you this blind man's counsel, trusting to your clear judgment.
  footnotes:
    - 'Sageum River (沙斤川): A riverside location near the departure point.'
    - 'Spring''s warmth (春暉) and the wind through trees (風樹): Classical allusions expressing the irreplaceable duty of filial service and the tragedy of being unable to fulfill it.'
    - 'The Sage (聖人): Confucius, who established the ritual mourning system.'
    - 'Zi Xia (子夏): A disciple of Confucius who went blind from grief after losing his son, and was criticized by the sage tradition for allowing emotion to override propriety.'
    - The three categories of untimely death refer to children who die before reaching adulthood, for whom modified mourning rites apply.
    - 'Chen Quanfei (陳去非): A Song dynasty poet known for expressing the paradox of knowing that grief is transient yet being unable to resist it.'
